<p><b>Khalil Gibran</b> (born <b>Gibrān Khalīl Gibrān bin Mikhā'īl bin Sa'ad</b>; <a href="/wiki/Arabic_language" title="Arabic language">Arabic</a> <span lang="ar" xml:lang="ar">جبران خليل جبران بن ميکائيل بن سعد</span>), (January 6, 1883 – April 10, 1931) was a <a href="/wiki/Lebanese_American" title="Lebanese American">Lebanese American</a> <a href="/wiki/Artist" title="Artist">artist</a>, <a href="/wiki/Poet" title="Poet">poet</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Writer" title="Writer">writer</a>. Born in the town of <a href="/wiki/Bsharri" title="Bsharri">Bsharri</a> in modern-day <a href="/wiki/Lebanon" title="Lebanon">Lebanon</a> (then part of <a href="/wiki/Ottoman_Syria" title="Ottoman Syria">Ottoman Syria</a>), as a young man he emigrated with his family to the <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">United States</a> where he studied art and began his literary career. He is chiefly known for his 1923 book <i><a href="/wiki/The_Prophet_(book)" title="The Prophet (book)">The Prophet</a></i>, a series of philosophical essays written in <a href="/wiki/English_language" title="English language">English</a> prose. An early example of <a href="/w/index.php?title=Inspirational_literature&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Inspirational literature (page does not exist)">inspirational literature</a>, the book sold well despite a cool critical reception, and became extremely popular in <a href="/wiki/Counterculture_of_the_1960s" title="Counterculture of the 1960s">1960s counterculture</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-NY-Jan-08_0-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NY-Jan-08-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
